  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is typically defined as the process of making illegally-obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex financial transactions. Legal definitions can vary between jurisdictions, but generally include:\n\n1. Three core stages:\n- Placement (introducing illegal funds into financial system)\n- Layering (concealing source through complex transactions)\n- Integration (making funds appear legitimate)\n\n2. Key elements usually include:\n- Knowingly concealing or transferring proceeds from criminal activity\n- Attempting to disguise the origin of illegally obtained funds\n- Conducting financial transactions designed to hide illegal sources\n- Engaging in transactions to avoid reporting requirements\n\n3. Common legal criteria:\n- Intent to disguise criminal proceeds\n- Knowledge that funds originate from illegal activities\n- Deliberate efforts to make funds appear legitimate\n\nThe specific definitions and penalties vary by country, with most developed nations having comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) statutes.\n\nWould you like more detailed information about specific legal frameworks or jurisdictional approaches?",
